import sqlite3
import pandas

print("Part 1")
# Using SQL compute a relation containing the total payroll 
# and winning percentage (number of wins / number of games * 100) 
# for each team (that is, for each teamID and yearID combination). 
# You should include other columns that will help when performing EDA 
# later on (e.g., franchise ids, number of wins, number of games).

sqlite_file = 'lahman2014.sqlite'
conn = sqlite3.connect(sqlite_file)

salary_query = "SELECT teamID, yearID, sum(salary) as total_payroll FROM Salaries GROUP BY teamID,yearID ORDER BY teamID" 
team_salaries = pandas.read_sql(salary_query, conn)
team_salaries.head()

win_percentage = "SELECT teamID, yearID,sum(W) as total_wins, sum(W)+sum(L) as total_games, 100*CAST(sum(W) AS float)/(sum(W)+sum(L)) as 'win_rate', franchID FROM teams \
       GROUP BY teamID,yearID ORDER BY teamID"
winnings = pandas.read_sql(win_percentage, conn)

# Combine team_salaries and winnnings "compute relation"
#The INNER JOINS: Matching records only

# Problem 1:
print("Problem 1: \nUse .merge function to merge the winnings and team_salaries table, as it will account for all missing data entries\n")
combined = team_salaries.merge(winnings, left_on = ["teamID","yearID"], right_on = ["teamID","yearID"])
combined

# Problem 2
# Write code to produce plots that illustrate the distribution of payrolls across teams conditioned on time (from 1990-2014).

# Make a graph and add all data from all teams from 1990-2014 to it

# Sort yearID's and get 1990-2014 teams
years = combined.sort_values("yearID")
years = years.loc[years["yearID"] >= 1990]

# need year, team, and total_payroll for graphs

to_plot = years[["yearID", "teamID", "total_payroll"]]
teams = to_plot["teamID"].drop_duplicates()

for i in teams:
    tt = to_plot.groupby(['teamID']).get_group(i)
    plt.plot(tt.yearID, tt.total_payroll, color = "green") 
    plt.title("Total Payroll for " + i + " from 1990-2014") 
    # Starts at first year with data
    plt.xlabel("Year")
    plt.ylabel("Payroll")
    plt.show()

print("\nProblem 4")
# Write code to discretize year into five time periods 
# (you can use pandas.cut to accomplish this) and then make a scatterplot 
# showing mean winning percentage (y-axis) vs. mean payroll (x-axis) 
# for each of the five time periods. You could add a regression line 
# (using, e.g., NumPy's polyfit) in each scatter plot to ease interpretation.

print("Plot a graph for each time period")

bins = [1990,1995,2000,2005,2010,2015]
combined["period"] = pandas.cut(combined.yearID, bins, labels = ["p1", "p2", "p3", "p4", "p5"])

periods = combined[["period","total_payroll","teamID", "win_rate"]]
periods = periods.groupby(["period","teamID"],as_index=False).mean()

# Fill NaN 
periods.win_rate.fillna(periods.win_rate.mean(),inplace=True)
periods.total_payroll.fillna(periods.total_payroll.mean(),inplace=True)

groups = periods.groupby("period")

for key, g in groups:
    g.plot(kind='scatter', x='total_payroll', y='win_rate', marker='o', s = 50, color = "red")
    plt.title("Period " + key[1] +"'s Average Winning % vs. Average Payroll")
    plt.set_xlabel = "Average Payroll"
    plt.set_ylabel = "Average Winning %"
    
    for i, txt in enumerate(periods.teamID):
        
        plt.annotate(txt, (periods.total_payroll[i], periods.win_rate[i]), xytext=(1, 1),
        textcoords="offset points",
        fontsize="12",
        color="green")


#What can you say about team payrolls across these periods? 
#Are there any teams that standout as being particularly good at
#paying for wins across these time periods? What can you say about
#the Oakland A's spending efficiency across these time periods

print("\n\nWe see that NYA has a pretty large payroll starting in period 2, and continues to have a substantially high win percentage.")
print("ATL also has very high winning percentages even with smaller payrolls.")
print("OAK, on the other hand, has a smaller average payroll and yet has a pretty high win rate %, which is comparable to NYA.")
print("Therefore, we can conclude that OAK is very efficient with their spending.")

print("Problem 5")

avg_payroll = (combined[["yearID","total_payroll"]].groupby("yearID")).mean()
avg_payroll.columns = ["avg_payroll"]

std_dev = (combined[["yearID","total_payroll"]].groupby("yearID")).std()
std_dev.columns = ["std_dev"]

to_add = []

for index,row in combined.iterrows():
    to_add.append((row['total_payroll'] - avg_payroll['avg_payroll'][row["yearID"]]) / std_dev["std_dev"][row["yearID"]])

combined["std_payroll"] = to_add
combined
